<p><span class="speaker">William Faulkner</span>Yes, ma'am.</p>
<p><span class="speaker">Unidentified participant</span>As a student who always had to struggle through literature courses trying
                    to dig out the meanings of things which seemed obvious to other people, I'd be
                    curious to know if, as a writer,  you sort of do have these messages in mind,
                    greater ideas which the English teachers and so forth always produce so readily,
                    and some of the <span class="unclear tooltip" title="Text was unclear">[students]</span>
                    <span class="event tooltip" title="There was some audience laughter happening">[audience laughter]</span> can't find them anywhere.</p>
<p><span class="speaker">William Faulkner</span>No'm, not really. The writer is writing about people. He has got to use
                    the tools he has, which is his own experience, his own observation, and out of
                    that, in the course of&mdash;of twenty-one, twenty-two years it takes to
                    mature, then whatever years after that, come the opinions. He doesn't have to
                    stop and say, "Now, this is what I believe." It's there. He don't know he's
                    got it. Then when he writes, suddenly something&mdash;somebody says
                    something, he says, "Well, yes, that's so. That's what I believe, too." He
                    didn't put that in the character's mouth. The character said, "This is what I
                    think." The writer says, "Yes, I agree with you." That he is too busy dealing
                    with people to have time to deliver messages to anyone. The messages happen
                    just by chance. That he is interested in&mdash;in creating flesh and blood
                    people to do the&mdash;the tragic or the comic things which people do
                    for&mdash;for pleasure. That is, I think that one should read for pleasure,
                    that one doesn't necessarily have to read for pleasure, but I myself read for
                    pleasure, not for ideas.  That if it's&mdash;I've got to hunt around in a book
                    to&mdash;looking for an idea, then I'd rather do something else. I'd rather
                    do something that's more fun than that. It won't be reading.
                </p>
